<h2>Why Mothers Are Underserved by Mental Health Care</h2>
<p>Mothers are among the most psychologically burdened groups in modern society — managing primary caregiving, professional roles, domestic labour, and their own wellbeing simultaneously, often in contexts where asking for help carries stigma ("good mothers cope"). The result: significant rates of depression, anxiety, burnout, and identity disruption that go unaddressed for years.</p>

<p>Online therapy is particularly valuable for mothers precisely because it removes the barriers that most impede access: the need for childcare to attend an appointment, the commute, the fixed schedule. Sessions can happen from home, during nap time, in a parked car — wherever private space can be found.</p>

<h2>Postpartum Depression and Anxiety</h2>
<p>Perinatal mood and anxiety disorders (PMADs) affect 1 in 5 mothers during pregnancy or within the first year postpartum. Postpartum depression is the most well-known, but postpartum anxiety, OCD, PTSD (from birth trauma), and psychosis also occur and are undertreated.</p>

<p>PMADs are not caused by being a bad mother or not bonding adequately — they are mood disorders triggered by the profound hormonal, sleep, identity, and relational changes of the perinatal period. They respond to therapy, medication, or both.</p>

<p>CBT for postpartum depression has strong evidence. It addresses the specific thought patterns common in PMAD — "I'm a bad mother," "I don't feel the way I should," "Something is wrong with me" — alongside the behavioural withdrawal and isolation that deepen depressed mood.</p>

<h2>Maternal Burnout</h2>
<p>Maternal burnout is increasingly recognised as distinct from general burnout — characterised by intense exhaustion related specifically to the parenting role, emotional distance from one's children (that generates guilt, amplifying the burnout), and reduced sense of efficacy as a parent. It's most common in mothers with perfectionistic standards for parenting, limited social support, and heavy caregiving loads.</p>

<p>Therapy addresses the cognitive component (unrealistic parenting standards, guilt cycles), the emotional component (grief for the pre-child self, resentment that generates shame), and the practical component (support systems, expectations, division of labour).</p>

<h2>Identity and the Transition to Motherhood</h2>
<p>Matrescence — the psychological process of becoming a mother — is a profound identity transition that receives inadequate cultural attention. Many women experience the loss of a previous identity, ambivalence about motherhood (which is normal but rarely discussed), and difficulty integrating the mother role with the rest of who they are.</p>

<p>Therapy provides a space to process this transition without judgment — to hold ambivalence, grieve losses, integrate the new identity, and rebuild a sense of self that includes but isn't entirely consumed by motherhood.</p>

<h2>Relationship Challenges</h2>
<p>The transition to parenthood is the most common precipitant of relationship distress in couples. The shift in roles, sleep deprivation, sexual changes, and differing parenting approaches generate friction that often goes unaddressed until it becomes severe. Individual therapy for mothers, couples therapy, or both, addresses this specifically.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<p><strong>Can I be in therapy and breastfeed?</strong><br/>
Yes. Therapy doesn't interfere with breastfeeding. If medication is also being considered, specific medication choices are made with breastfeeding in mind — many SSRIs are compatible with breastfeeding, but this is a conversation with a prescriber.</p>

<p><strong>My children need me present. Is it selfish to do therapy for myself?</strong><br/>
The opposite. Untreated maternal depression and anxiety affect children's development, attachment, and long-term mental health. Caring for your mental health is caring for your children.</p>

<p><strong>I'm a mother with older children, not a new parent. Is therapy still relevant?</strong><br/>
Absolutely. Parenting stress, maternal identity issues, burnout, and the specific challenges of different developmental stages (adolescent children, empty nest) all have a meaningful therapeutic context.</p>

